## 4. Key Security & Quality Findings

> [!WARNING]
> ### 1. Missing Role-Based Authorization Checks
> Although the system supports roles (`RECRUITER` and `CANDIDATE`) and stores them in the JWT token (as a claim and as authorities prefixed with `ROLE_`), **role authorization is never enforced on endpoints**. 
> - A user registered as a `CANDIDATE` can successfully hit `POST /api/jobs/post` to create a job.
> - A user registered as a `RECRUITER` can successfully hit `POST /api/applications/apply/{jobId}` to apply to a job.
> - **Impact:** High security vulnerability allowing users to perform actions outside their designated organizational role.

> [!CAUTION]
> ### 2. Plaintext Secrets & Hardcoded Connection Credentials
> Sensitive configurations are exposed in [application.properties](file:///c:/projects/smart-hiring/src/main/resources/application.properties):
> - The PostgreSQL datasource URL contains connection credentials, hostnames, and passwords in plaintext.
> - The JWT signing secret is hardcoded as `mySecretKey123456789012345678901234567890`.
> - **Impact:** Severe credential exposure if this code is committed to a public repository.

> [!WARNING]
> ### 3. CORS Configuration Conflict
> - [SecurityConfig.java](file:///c:/projects/smart-hiring/src/main/java/com/hire/smart/hiring/security/SecurityConfig.java) specifies precise allowed origins (`http://localhost:5173`, `http://localhost:5174`) and allows credentials (`config.setAllowCredentials(true)`).
> - However, the controller classes ([AuthController](file:///c:/projects/smart-hiring/src/main/java/com/hire/smart/hiring/controller/AuthController.java), [JobController](file:///c:/projects/smart-hiring/src/main/java/com/hire/smart/hiring/controller/JobController.java), [ApplicationController](file:///c:/projects/smart-hiring/src/main/java/com/hire/smart/hiring/controller/ApplicationController.java)) carry `@CrossOrigin(origins = "*")`.
> - **Impact:** Modern browsers block requests containing credentials (e.g. `Authorization` headers) when the server specifies `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`. The controller level `@CrossOrigin` overrides or conflicts with Spring Security's config and may cause CORS errors on the frontend.

> [!NOTE]
> ### 4. Generic Exceptions & Lack of Global Error Handler
> Service classes throw generic `RuntimeException` (e.g., `throw new RuntimeException("Email already registered!");`).
> - **Impact:** In Spring Boot, uncaught `RuntimeException`s yield a generic HTTP 500 error response status. Standard errors like "Already applied to this job" should return a HTTP 400 Bad Request, and unauthorized operations (like deleting a job owned by someone else) should return HTTP 403 Forbidden.

